column1: it's weird how this journey has been. everyone around me spoke of how important the first ever time is supposed to be. i didn't even have a first ever time to talk about. because i don't even know what it felt like. i mean i wonder if i even felt anything.
teenage is the time for realisations and confusions they said. little did i know my life as i knew it was going to go for a toss. the moment i heard those words from my bio teachers mouth
column2: i remember actually having experienced it. everything was just as she described. the difference was i was a child
column3: and he was an old man. how was i supposed to know? first thing i felt was disgust. not towards him
column4: but towards myself. for days i pondered if it was me. was it me who somehow showed a *baby way* of enticing him? or was there even a *baby way* of doing that? hell i knew i didn't even know how to flirt. i still don't. how did i become the reason why it happened? not once

column2: but probably the wrong way. i began to think i deserved it. and it all made sense to me. my already twisted mind began to identify how falling prey to someone became a pattern in my life. it didn't always have to be sexual. but i knew i was ending up his victim each time i tried to be myself.

column1: 287223;instagram;2018-10-17 15:27:01;FALSE;"in observance of domestic violence awareness month

when i was in istanbul the past week i realized how oppressed are women in other nations. we are allowed to speak and i am going to do just such. i have never been so patronized as i was in that city. women are treated as inferior creatures. whenever i would stand up for myself and say no to anything

column1: 287272;instagram;2018-10-17 15:13:06;FALSE;"today the ceo of our local hospital will be receiving a healthcare hero award today. this is a really hard pill for myself and many other women in this community to swallow.
the ceo lead the way to take over the other two local hospitals we used to have creating a monopoly situation in town and removing choices for birthing women specifically.

women now have to travel a minimum of 45 minutes to receive care if they wish to pursue a vaginal birth after cesarean.  the hospital refuses to engage in conversations about how this puts women at risk and how many families who do not have the financial means can not access this type of care.

while the illegal ban remains in place under the leadership of ron werft the ceo some women have been afforded the privilege to have a vaginal birth after cesarean at cottage with the support of staff.  that begs the question why are some women given the choice and others not? why is it that no one in santa barbara cottage hospital administration is willing to have a conversation about how this affects our community?

they built a new birthing center wing yet didn‚Äôt think to put the nicu next to the mothers who should be having skin to skin contact with their sweet babies. and yet we are still waiting for the nicu to be moved next to the mothers. how is this man who is over all of this a hero to the women and families of this town?
note: the hospital is full of amazing employees who go above and beyond and who have no control over protocol that hurts people.

column1: 287339;instagram;2018-10-17 14:34:44;FALSE;"the first time i can consciously remember feeling like men were not safe was when i was four or five years old.
we were spending some time by my grandmother in the summer time and i was out in the garden and caught a butterfly by myself for the first time ü¶ã
i ran into the house screaming with excitement calling for my mom to tell her and a male family member was on the phone. my happiness
column2: exuberance and loudness disturbed his phone call so he kicked me
column3: flinging my little body onto the floor.

column1: my mother grabbed me and screamed at him. she protected me as best as she could but the damage was already done. i learned in that moment that men were not safe. ¬∞
it's bizarre how these things stay with you that at 30 years old writing about this experience could still evoke an emotional reaction in me.
i know now that there are good men out there and i am working through these damaging belief systems working with professionals unreavling them bit by bit and replacing them with healthier truths.
however i was standing on the street recently at night and there were 3 men around me
column2: all minding their own business doing their own things but i felt so un-safe and uncomfortable that i just came back upstairs. a man also accosted me and tried to hug me even though i told him not to touch me and he was making me uncomfortable on the street and i literally ran away from him. sometimes men make women feel uncomfortable without even knowing.

column1: what i am trying to say is be conscious of the people you allow your children to spend time with.
experiences we have when we are small can stay with us and cause damage long after.
little ones need us to protect them until they can protect themselves. our pets need us to protect them all the time üê∂
i am not trying to demonize men. i am sure most of the men reading this will be horrified by the story. i am just sharing my experiences to create awareness and bring about conversation and healing.
if you have a similar story or feel compelled to share something with me please feel free to dm me. let's chat. i'm listening.

we need to pay special attention to where our mind goes. does our mind revert into victim based thinking? victim based thinking is rooted in:
notice your thoughts. do they drift to feeling angry and being fearful about the future? do you have thoughts like:

these thoughts are rooted in victim-based thinking. thoughts like:
‚Äòi can‚Äôt and i won‚Äôt‚Äô live here.

column2: blame others and stay backed in our corner.

column1: sometimes our anger is even justified. even if your anger is validated

column1: the next step in your mental evolution is to become a survivor. a survivor is someone who acknowledges the struggle but thinks about it differently. thoughts that live here are:

column1: 287410;instagram;2018-10-17 13:49:29;FALSE;"i remember the shock. the denial.  i remember praying and feeling like god didn‚Äôt hear me. i remember the cold voice of the doctor saying this pregnancy wasn‚Äôt viable.
new wife. new career. new mom. or so we thought. i demanded a second opinion and was sure the dr. was mistaken. new week
column3: same verdict. we were devastated. those next few weeks were exhausting. soon enough we were pregnant again with grace
column4: but robbed of the joy. i don‚Äôt think you are ever the same after loss. afraid to celebrate. afraid to have hope. afraid to believe everything is fine until the day she was finally in my arms.

column1: fast forward two years later and we were ecstatic grace was going to be a big sister. this time we had hope. we had proof we could carry a healthy child. we then had news we never wanted to hear again. no heartbeat. i vividly remember jay looking at me and saying

all i could think was this is my fault. my body f****d up again. he was happy with one child.... but no. i couldn‚Äôt leave well enough alone. i am sure that these things are far from how he felt. however
column2: i instantly felt the weight of the world in my shoulders. after all

column1: i remember feeling guilty for how broken hearted i was losing a baby when i had a healthy girl at home. i remember the kindness of friends and the silence of others.
i remember the physical pain and the emotional exhaustion. how hard it was to get out of bed when i wanted to scream at everyone i saw that my baby was gone.
and i remember jay crying and crying.
the months after were painful. there were fights

column1: 287493;instagram;2018-10-17 13:17:16;FALSE;no one should do anything. #stereotyping . seeing all women as saintly and righteous victims reminds me of the madonna-whore complex discovered by #sigmundfreud (yes that's what he called it) . according to freud someone who views women this way sees them as either pure and virtuous or as something completely debased
column2: messed up. this video above is just a modern way of perpetuating that complex: some ppl will see all women as always right/madonnas
column3: and others will see all women as always wrong or not right enough. speaking as someone who has definitely faced harassment: all claims of anything must be investigated objectively.  i'm uncomfortable with ppl lumping all women into one category whether it's good or bad. all women are not liars but all women are not honest either. objectivity must be encouraged. it's easy to analyze if a narrative makes logical sense or if it seems to be missing essential links. all men cannot be lumped into the same category either
column4: good or bad. this video is a bit too simplistic- this kind of 'good' stereotyping of women usually generates a backlash from idiots and perhaps rightly so
column5: though they are not eloquent enough to explain what made them uncomfortable. a victim can be male or female. on a sidenote: someday guys will wake up and realize how much they have been peer pressured by male friends and /or by the women in their lives to sacrifice their preferences or boundaries -- all for the sake of either being cool

column1: 287505;instagram;2018-10-17 11:42:22;FALSE;"@lucyhale opens up about sexual harassment in her own home. full story in link in bio.

i moved to sydney alone when i was 18 years old. i was there for university and also for new job prospects in the city. i was from a small town so living in a big city was all very new to me. i found a cheap share house to live in at the time with people i didn‚Äôt know that were of similar age to me. my housemates were nice but we were all so busy running in and out of the house that we hardly really saw each other. i noticed one of my housemates always looking at me and staring at me from afar. i‚Äôd just ignore it usually. the longer i stayed at the house however the more comfortable he became around me. sometimes he‚Äôd whistle at me when i‚Äôd walk from the bathroom to my room. or he‚Äôd make lame catcall comments when we were both in the kitchen. what really drew the line for me was when he slapped me across the butt as i walked past him through the hallway. i was shocked
column2: i didn‚Äôt know how to respond. i was so angry. angry for weeks. he continued this harassment every chance he had. until i realised enough was enough and moved out. i look back and kept saying to myself. why didn‚Äôt you say anything? why didn‚Äôt you do anything lucy? i think because i wasn‚Äôt confident back then to stand up for myself. i wasn‚Äôt sure whether anyone could take me seriously. i‚Äôm so glad there are movements like #metoo and #iamasurvivor because it creates power and encourages confidence and strength to stand up for what you believe in and to talk about how you truly feel. i hope this helps other women out there fight for their rights. @__iamasurvivor__";;en;#MeToo

column1: #nieuwsuur is mee gaan stappen met sulaika en haar nichtje kristel. tijdens het uitgaan hebben ze last van jongens die over hun grenzen gaan. ook raadslid tanya #hoogwerf van leefbaar rotterdam zegt zich ernstige zorgen te maken over seksueel geweld in het uitgaansleven. ze ging samen met de politie de straat op en zegt daarover  dat mannen als groepjes hyena‚Äôs om de vrouwen heen gaan staan.
uit het onderzoek blijkt ook dat 77  procent van de vrouwelijke bezoekers de afgelopen twaalf maanden last heeft gehad van #seksueel_geweld. en 90 procent past daarop haar gedrag aan. zo ook kristel

column1: 287720;instagram;2018-10-17 11:04:04;FALSE;isn‚Äôt it awesome when you can give someone a gift that changes their life? how would it feel if you bought a gift for someone that will change their life & kept it to yourself? what if it was because you‚Äôre scared of what they‚Äôll think of it & you? seems kind of silly right? my friend
column2: we do this every day not sharing our god given gifts & talents. instead
column3: we allow them to rot away in the attic of our comfort zones. and yup
column4: we do this because we‚Äôre scared. what could your gifts possibly do? well
column5: think of that person who literally saved/changed your life by sharing their gifts. what would of happened if they hid their gift out of fear? where would you be? for me back in my dark days
column6: a big influence was @jannarden her music has this beautiful ability to break your heart & fix it in 3 mins flat. her music showed me the beauty of how to feel & heal. her writings taught me that being raw & vulnerable is a strength. her bravery to share her ups & downs showed me the power of sharing mine. she taught me the beauty of showing up imperfectly
column7: perfect. that not everyone will be into what you have to offer or how you present it but to share it anyway. her humour taught me that no matter how bleak life looked you could always find laughter & hope. i am continuously thankful that jann chooses to contribute her gifts to the world. i can‚Äôt imagine how much harder or none existent my life would of been if warriors like her hadn‚Äôt paved the way already. someone needs our offerings the exact same way we needed the gifts of others. we need to stop playing small. dust off those wonderful gifts & get them out there. there are people who need them. my hopes in sharing this today is that you can see clearly too that the world isn‚Äôt just waiting for your unique gifts & abilities
column8: it needs them urgently. whenever fear knocks at our door

column1: 287796;instagram;2018-10-17 09:08:09;FALSE;"what 11 women journalists have accused mj akbar
india‚Äôs #metoo chorus is being heard from every corner of the country. the campaign took india with a storm with women naming out men who sexually harassed them.
so far 11 allegations have emerged against journalist-turned- politician and bjp minister  mj akbar. akbar‚Äôs colleagues
column2: including smriti irani and maneka gandhi
column3: have acknowledged the online testimonies against him and have called for a probe.

column1: akbar was first accused by journalist priya ramani
column2: who had written about him in an article she wrote for vogue a year ago with exposing his name. as the #metoo movement began to gain momentum
column3: priya now made it clear that the article was about akbar‚Äôs misconducts.priya recounts how akbar interviewed her in a hotel
column4: offered her a drink (which she refused)
column5: asked her to sit next to him on the bed and even sang her romantic hindi songs.

column1: another uk-based journalist ruth david recounted how akbar started calling her into his office which was a room with a big wooden door which ensured no one could hear or see what was going on inside.she further recalled how he stood behind and offered massages and would try to kiss her. ‚Äúakbar tried to kiss me against my will

a us-based journalist has come forward to accuse akbar of sexual harassment. cnn scribe majlie de puy kamp has revealed that she was sexually harassed by akbar in 2007 when she was an 18-year-old intern. sharing the incident on twitter
column2: kamp wrote: ‚Äúakbar shoved his 55-year-old tongue down my 18-year-old throat.‚Äù case 4:

column2: who see a little kid sitting alone on the chair. without wasting time a group of 5 or more boys go towards the child and ask her questions
column3: now the child is just 7 and does not remember most of it but she will never forget the rest of that night for her whole life. because some scars never fade.

column1: what they did was unthinkable. that night the child wore one of her favourite pink dresses. the boys started touching her one after another and soon their hands moved to places where they shouldn't and now she does not remember who's hands touched which part of hers but one of the hands entered her undergarments and touched her so called 'shame shame area' and soon his fingers travelled deep within and the pain was unbearable. she cried but was too afraid to talk about it to anyone.

don't dare to say that she asked for it because she does not remember all of it but she gets the nightmares every single time and cries because after that night crying was all she could do. and people still ask her why she does not like the colour pink.

column2: for one such incident is not enough to break a girl)
